<center>Islam </center>\n\nIslam may be a good fit for you.\n\nIslam is a still a popular religion today. It is a monotheistic religion deriving from Judaism and Christianity. \n\nFrom the 1400s to 1700s, you could find many Muslims in Africa and the Middle East. India under the Mughal Empire was an Indian empire ruled by a Muslim minority. The ruler Akbar sought to reconcicle Islam with Hinduism, but later rulers disliked the mixing of the religions. \n\n[[Back to beginning|3]]\n[[Table of Contents|Start]]

<center>Christianity </center>\n\nYou may find Christianity to be to your liking. It is a monotheistic religion that is based on Jewish beliefs. \n\nChristianity was concentrated in Europe from the 1400s to 1700s. There were (and are) many branches of this religion, including but not limited to Catholicism, Protestantism, Lutheranism, Puritanism, and Orthodoxy. You can find many Orthodox Christians in Russia, and many of the English people who colonized the Americas were Pilgrims and Puritans. \n\nMartin Luther began a movement to reform the Church in Europe during the Reformation. If joining a large Church is not to your taste, you can choose to believe in a more modest version of Christianity. Many other branches were (and are) available to pick from, giving plenty of options for any convert.\n\n[[Back to beginning|3]]\n[[Table of Contents|Start]]

/% shinto%/\n<center> Shintoism</center>\n\nShintoism is an Asian religion with beliefs of spirituality in nature, as well as multiple deities of natural origin. It includes many shrines and simple places of worship in rural places. \n\n[[Back to beginning|3]]\n[[Table of Contents|Start]]

Obviously, you're probably not religious. I doubt you would be pleased with any religion I present to you. However, if you really like order and social stratification, you may like Confucianism. /%Hindu %/<center>Hinduism</center>\n\nIf you like worshiping hundreds upon hundreds of gods, you'll probably get a kick out of Hinduism. It is a polytheistic religion encompassing many regions of India and incorporating some elements of Buddhism as well.\n\nDuring Akbar's reign of the Mughal Empire, Hinduism, besides other religions, were very tolerated. However, later rulers disliked religions besides Islam.\n\n[[Back to beginning|3]]\n[[Table of Contents|Start]]

This is generally what you have translated from your team's driver's interactions with you. This also happens to be what you often hear from your team speaking to said driver. \n\nTherefore, it was not a big surprise to you when you came across his corpse in a section of the field far from the plantation owner's residence. \n\nAs unpopular as he was, justice must be served. The prime suspects in this case, three people, you included, have been brought to the plantation owner's house, under the watchful eye of a security guard. \n\n[[Next|d7]]\n\n[[(Click here to go back one page.)|d5]]\n\n[[(Click here to go back to the very beginning of this particular story.)|5]]
There are three people the plantation owner suspects of killing the driver. One of them is you. However, he's agitated, pacing around the room, and probably is only looking for someone to blame. You doubt he'll be able to figure out who it really was if no one confesses.\n\nYou sit in a cheap wooden chair. Next to you are Banana, and the quiet man. The security guard stays alert as the plantation owner's adult son observes the scene.\n\nYou're certain that the person who did it was...\n\n[[Banana.|d8a]]\n\n[[the quiet man.|d8b]]\n\n[[you.|d8c]]

You know it will get hot while you're out working in the fields. \tSince the plantation owner finds you guilty, you are sent to the flogging post. You're pretty sure he would kill you if he wasn't so cheap. That's good for you, because while flogging hurts the back, your legs are still fine. <center>Confucianism</center>\nConfucianism is less of a religion and more of a philosophy. It emphasizes strict, orderly relationships between different types of people. It does include the concept of heaven, but the philosophy itself is not really a religion. Most Chinese beliefs include some form of ancestor worship, as well.\n\n[[Back to beginning|3]]\n[[Table of Contents|Start]]

Would you prefer...\n\n[[The oldest, more ancient religion?|f2aa]]\n\n[[A slightly newer, more varied religion?|f2ab]]\n\n[[The "most complete" version of a religion, with more material to study and admire?|f2ac]]
<center>Buddhism</center>\n\nBuddhism is a religion that focuses on the individual path to nirvana. Unless you choose Mahayana Buddhism, there is no worship of particular figures. It is a very modest religion that requires discipline and self control. \n\nBuddhism can be found in India, and is also popular in some regions of Asia, notably Mahayana Buddhism in general, and Zen Buddhism in Japan.\n\n[[Back to beginning|3]]\n[[Table of Contents|Start]]

<center> @@font-size:x-large;Calculus@@</center>\nCalculus has made its way onto this list because I like math. It's also something I'm likely going to have to pay for to study in college, which makes it very important.\n\nAccording to the History of Calculus website, the two major creators of calculus are Sir Isaac Newton and Gottfried Wilhelm von Leibniz. They both had different takes on the subject, but Leibniz recorded his findings in a more organized fashion, so more of his notation is used today.\n\n[[Back|2]]\n[[{{{#}}}9 |tt9]]

<center> @@font-size:x-large;Compound Microscopes@@</center>\n\nOne important contribution to science was the compound microscope. People had already created lenses and eyeglasses, but Zacharias and Hans Jansen were the first, in the 1590s, to combine several lenses in a tube and find that it magnified the object viewed at the other end of the tube. They weren't very clear images, nor were they extremely useful, achieving about nine times as large an image.\n\nLater, Anton van Leeuwenhoek made a much better compound microscope in the 17th century that was able to reach 270 times. He used his microscopes to study tiny organisms and blood vessels (A complete Microscope History).\n\n[img[first-optical-microscope]]\n//What one of the first microscopes might have looked like.//\nNobel Prize Time Line for Microscopes:\n{{{http://www.nobelprize.org/educational/physics/microscopes/timeline/}}}\n[[Back|tt10]]\n[[{{{#}}}8: |tt8]]
<center> @@font-size:x-large; Hypodermic Syringes@@ </center>\n\nHypodermic syringes are an indispensable part of modern medicine. Whether they are used for the injection of a vaccine, sedative, or medicine, most people in industrialized countries will have experienced it at least once, if not many more times, in their lives. \n\nThough there have been syringe-like devices prior to the 1600s, usually for the not so glorious purpose of administering clysters, the most likely first recorded use of a syringe for intravaneous injection in Britain was Christopher Wren, in the year 1657. Wren is also known for his work in architecture. \n[img[needles]]\n<span style ="font-size:small;">//Caption reads: "Fig. 1 : Evolution of syringe in the history of medicine. A, A model of primitive enema syringe. The pressure bulb used to be made from animal bladder and the quill from ivory or bamboo. Much later, in the seventeenth century, elastic bulb and bottle made from rubber gum replaced the use of animal bladder. B, A model of the seventeenth century syringe. Wren used a similar type of syringe for his experiments of intravenous injections. C, A model of the nineteenth century syringe. Charles Sage received patent on January 10, 1843 for the model shown. D, A model of early hypodermic syringe. A similar type of syringe was used by Alexander Wood. E, A watch chain syringe (graduated) used mainly for subcutaneous injection in the late nineteenth century. Marketted by Messers. Joseph Wood & Co. F, Multipurpose syringe of Pavez with different types of canulae.//</span>\nAccording to //Evolution of Medical Application of Syringe//, Wren used a simple syringe composed of a quill and a bladder to pump liquids, like wine, into the veins of dogs. His attempt to use it on a human failed. His syringe was quite new for his time, but was inelegant to use on living people. Throughout the 17th century, syringes were used mostly on animals and dead people.\n\n[img[charriere_syringe_1]]\n//A syringe set, likely from the 1870s.//\n[[Back|tt9]]\n[[{{{#}}}7: |tt7]]

<center>@@font-size:x-large;#3: Screws and the Screwdriver@@</center>\nScrews were used by the Romans, and possibly by people before them. However, their screws were considerably large, and powered by human or animal labor. \n\nScrewdrivers were probably invented in Germany or France in the late 1400s, but it is unknown who made the first screwdriver. Screws were used in armor as well as firearms. They could hold up well when used in firearms. \n\nThe first attempt to produce screwdrivers by machine was a technological success, and a commercial failure. In 1776, the English Wyatt brothers opened a factory that could produce screws quickly and accurately, but they were unable to make a successful business. People after them improved the idea and were able to make the business profitable. \n\n[img[rsz_screw_press_illustration]]\n\nToday, screwdrivers are one of the most important tools for assembling basically anything. The most popular type of screw is probably the Phillips screw, which was not invented until the 1930s. \n[[Back|tt4]]\n[[{{{#}}}2: |tt2]]\n
<center>@@font-size:x-large;#2 Gutenberg's Printing Press@@ </center>\nJohannes Gutenberg was not the first to use movable type, but he was the first to successfully commercially implement it. His printing press was designed similarly to wine presses, and it became an efficient way to print many books quickly and cheaply. The first examples of movable type are from China and Korea.\n\nHis quicker method of printing not only made printing faster, but cheap enough for people outside the nobility to afford. One of the most important books to spread outside the nobility was the Bible. When the peasant class began to become more literate, people objected to contradictions between the Bible and the Pope's authority. This led to events such as the Reformation, and Martin Luther spread his beliefs through printed material. \n\nGutenberg's press spread knowledge to thousands of people. Today, books are easily accessible and affordable, and nearly anyone can purchase books. \n\n[img[presse]] <span style=“text-align:right”>[img[setzkast]]</span>\n\n[[Back|tt3]]\n[[{{{#}}}1: |tt1]]
<center>@@font-size:x-large; #1: The Caravel@@ </center>\nAccording to the "History of the Caravel" webpage, it is speculated that the term "caravel" was derived from a smaller Arabic ship called a "qarib" with similar features, and that the caravel evolved from this ship into a bigger type of vessel. There is no clear exact caravel design, because of the many variants of the ship. However, the name is mentioned in a Portugese document dating to 1226. \n\nI chose this invention to be on this list because, even though it technically was not invented from the 1400-1700s, it was adapted for use in exploration by Henry the Navigator and the Portugese (Mariners' Museum website). Caravels were a maneuverable, adaptable vessel that helped the Portugese explore along the coast of West Africa.\n\nIn fact, two of Christopher Columbus's three ships were probably caravels, as well. These ships probably helped his crew to get to the New World and make contact with an unknown people, leading to the eventual conquests of native civilizations.\n\n<center>[img[15th_century_caravel]]</center>\n//Caravels could be rigged with square sails or lateen sails, depending on the situation. Portugese caravels had two or three masts, and used as cargo carriers, warships, patrol boats, or pirate ships (Mariners' Museum website).// \n\n[[Back|tt2]]\n[[Done|2]]
\n[img[political cartoon]]\n\nA political poster trying to convince African people to stand up to the king for allowing people to be sold into slavery.\n\nEspecially in the 1700s, many Africans were sold as slaves to work in sugar, indigo, and tobacco plantations overseas. Most faced harsh conditions and experiences. Many were prisoners of war, and some were kidnapped. African kings sold the prisoners of war they had taken from the lands they conquered. \n\n[[Next|p2]]
<center> @@font-size:x-large; Bristled Toothbrushes@@</center>\n\nMost cultures had some form of tool for dental hygiene for many years. Compared to the modern toothbrush, they don't seem very effective. Older civilizations used twigs to clean their teeth, for example. However, it is thought that in 15th century China, people began to make and use bristled toothbrushes of carved bone or wood and bristles.\n\nAccording to Colgate.com, the bristles were likely pig neck bristles. After the concept was spread to Europe, Europeans began doing the same with softer horsehairs or feathers. \n\nIn spite of the questionable hygiene of the materials, this was a big improvement for dental health. The use of natural bristles remained standard until the invention of nylon.\n<center> [img[toothbrush]]</center>\n<center>//A much nicer toothbrush, using synthetic materials.// </center> \n\n[[Back|tt8]]\n[[{{{#}}}6: |tt6]]
<center> @@font-size:x-large; Watches and Clocks@@ </center>\n\nThe first inventions to tell time include devices such as sundials, hourglasses, and candles. Clocks have been evolving rapidly since a Chinese inventor designed a water powered mechanical clock in the early 11th century. From that time to the present day, many of the advancements in clock making came from Europe. The addition of a minute hand was one such important innovation. Clocks began to use different parts, tell time more efficiently, and use small screws for better accuracy. In in the 1600s, glass was used to protect watches and keep more accurate time.\n\n<center>[img[clocks-1]]</center>\n\nClock history timeline: \n{{{http://www.historyofwatch.com/clock-history/clock-timeline/}}}\n\n[[Back|tt7]]\n[[{{{#}}}5: |tt5]]
<center> @@font-size:x-large; The Telescope@@ </center>\n\nAccording to NASA, in 1609, Galileo Galilei was the first to make a telescope for astronomy purposes. It was adapted from a Dutch eye glass maker's telescope. With his telescope, Galileo could study heliocentric theory and the movement of planets. Many of his theories were rejected by the Church. He lived and died in Italy. \n\nNational Geographic Telescope Timeline:\n{{{http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/2009/07/telescopes/telescopes-interactive}}}\n\n\n[[Back|tt6]]\n[[{{{#}}}4: |tt4]]\n
<center> @@font-size:x-large; Pencils@@</center>\nAccording to Pencils.com, the early pencils were made of graphite, not lead. Widespread use of graphite came around during the 1560s. Early graphite was wrapped with string to reinforce the mineral. Eventually it was encased in wood instead. \n\n<center>[img[pencil_history_centered_oldest_known_wood_cased_pencil]]</center>\n\nGermany was the first place to mass produce pencils, starting in 1662. Besides being easy to write with, anyone who goes to school has used a pencil at least once. Artists use colored pencils, and mass produced pencils today cost about 33 cents.\n\n\n[[Back|tt5]]\n[[{{{#}}}3: |tt3]]\n

/% daosim %/<center>Daoism</center>\nPerhaps you would enjoy Daoism. Daoism is a religion that emphasizes being one with nature. It advocates living a simple, honest life and understanding the roles of life and death. \n\nDaoism was relatively popular in China as a personal religion.\n\n[[Back to beginning|3]]\n[[Table of Contents|Start]]

\tThe quiet man always looked suspicious to you, and pretty intelligent. He probably is capable of planning a murder, and he could probably also pin it on someone else. His skin looks lighter than most. You're pretty sure that he has a white father, which would explain why he can understand more languages.\n\nThe plantation owner asks the three of you to confess what you know about the crime. He is translated by the quiet man.\n\nDo you...\n\n[[Rethink about who commited the crime.|d7]]\n\n[[Testify against the quiet man.|d9ba]]
\tAs much as you enjoy his company, you know that Banana killed the driver. It was for a good reason, too. The driver had often been harassing his wife. You don't doubt that it was in self defense; the driver was often inebriated and short tempered on the job. \n\n\tStill, he has a wife, and several young children. If he's blamed for this crime, it could ruin their lives. \n\n\tThe plantation owner asks the three of you to confess what you know about the crime. He is translated by the quiet man.\n\nDo you...\n\n[[Rethink about who committed the crime.|d7]]\n[[Testify against Banana.|d9a]]\n[[Say that you did it.|d9bb]]
\n[img[poster for lost slaves]]\n\nA poster trying to get people to return runaway slaves to a sugar plantation. \n\nWhen faced with harsh conditions on a plantation, many slaves tried to run away from their captors. Sometimes, they were successful, and joined communities of maroons. These bands of runaways were a thorn in the side of the plantation owners, and there wasn't much else to do besides make compromises. Some of these deals included not letting new runaways in their communities. Most plantation owners and slave owners disliked when slaves ran away, due to the expense of acquiring a new one. \n\n[[Next|p3]]
[img[cossacks]]\n\nAn Uncle Sam style ad for recruiting Christians to become Cossacks. \n\nThe Cossacks welcomed warriors who could hold their own, but didn't acccept people who didn't believe in Christ. They caused trouble for European nations, usually because they were hired and paid to guard borders and provide military service. Over time, Cossacks lost their independence and autonomy to Polish and then Russian rulers. \n\n[[Back to beginning|4]]

\tWell, you did it. You've never been good at lying so you simply tell the truth. Banana winces. You'll miss him. The quiet man looks surprised that you're so blunt about it. He makes you feel kind of stupid.\n\n[[Next|d9b]]
<center> Chinese Pottery </center>\n\n<center>[img[bluewhitepootpoot]] </center>\n//(1426–1435)\n<center>[img[chickenpootpoot]]</center>\n(1465–1487)\n<center>[img[feeshpootpoot]]</center>\n(1522–1566)//\n\nThe classic Chinese style of white and blue porcelain is instantly recognizable. It was coveted by other empires and exported as a valuable item. \n\nThe examples of Chinese porcelain here are much different from the examples of pottery from Japan. For one, the porcelain is nearly always a milky white, and adorned with intricate art and designs. The blue and white jar, with the dragon on the side, shows the details of the dragon's scales and the clouds. It makes it a much more aesthetically pleasing piece, and functions as both storage and art. \n\nChinese pottery also has vibrant colors, as seen in the cup with the chickens on it. There had to be multiple layers of color, which made the process longer and more complicated. \n\nThe pot with the fish on it happens to symbolize wealth, a key goal of probably any Chinese person you'll meet. The Chinese word for "fish" sounds a lot like "abundance". There are vivid colors that contrast with each other, besides the ever present blue. The symbolism is important; for similar reasons, the number 4 is considered unlucky because the word in Chinese sounds similar to "death".\n\nThe piece decorated with a dragon has the name of the emperor at the time written on it, which was a popular tradition in China. \n[[Back|6]]\n[[Japanese pottery -->|a2]]

There's one guy whose nickname is Banana. You enjoy his company, even if you don't say much. He helps you out carrying things, sometimes, and you do the same. It's nice to have someone you can rely on.\n\nAnother one, who you don't know as well, you don't have a nickname for. He's usually quiet, but seems to listen more intently to what the plantation owners are saying. He's more well mannered than most people here. You think he might be able to understand the plantation owners fairly well.\n\n[[Back|d4]]

<center> Japanese Pottery </center>//\n<center>[img[storage jayr]] </center>\n(1392–1573)\n<center>[img[tea bowl]] </center>\n(1516–1592)\n<center>[img[pootpootjarstone]] </center>\n(1573–1615)//\nThe Japanese Pottery, compared to the Chinese works, are much more plain looking. Instead of a shiny, smooth white porcelain, these pieces are neutral, duller hues flecked with different shades. They appear to be much simpler in their decorations, as well. The jar with the most decorations has only a few shapes painted onto it, where the Chinese works have intricate designs and bright colors against a white background. \n\nThe simple aesthetic was in part made more popular by followers of the tea ceremony. The cup (black) is also a piece that was intended for use with the tea ceremony. The cup was made by hand, without the use of a potter's wheel, and is intentionally made with an uneven surface and dull glaze. Compared to the Chinese pottery, it seems rather unrefined and boring. However, to the Japanese, these wares were used for tea ceremonies for their simplicity. All three pieces appear much more usable and sturdy than the pottery of the Chinese, which look rather delicate.\n\nThese works do not have visible inscriptions of rulers on them, either, where writing the name of the current ruler on the pottery was relatively popular in China. \n\n[[Back|a1]]

<center> Judaism</center>\n\nJudaism may be right up your alley. It is a monotheistic religion that Christianity and Islam are based upon. \n\nThere have been many Jews throughout history who contributed to the economy. There were plenty of Jewish bankers during the Renaissance in Europe. However, Jews also are some of the most picked on religious groups in history, being expelled from Iberia in the //reconquista//, and discriminated against and ejected from multiple countries. \n\n[[Back to beginning|3]]\n[[Table of Contents|Start]]
